<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-075-095 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 238 745</DOCID><JOURNAL>T H E Journal (Technological Horizons In Education)  Sept 1991 v19n2 pS6(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Encyclopedias and archives. (Model Applications)(IBM Multimediasupplement)andM;</TITLE><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Special-purpose encyclopedias can be created using multimedia andentire conventional encyclopedias can be compressed onto a singleCD-ROM and augmented with multimedia enhancements.andP;  For example,the 1991 New Grolier Electronic Encyclopedia contains the 21volumes of Academic American Encyclopedia including 33,000articles, 2,000 pictures and 30 minutes of CD-quality audio on aCD-ROM.andP;  The ultimate in multimedia technology presently is TheVideo Encyclopedia of the 20th Century, which provides originalfilm footage of the 2,338 most significant events of the centuryon 42 videodiscs, all of which could be used in student-directedmultimedia research reports.andP;  IBM and Winnebago Software arecollaborating to extend Winnebago's electronic card catalogingsystem to include multimedia segments.andP;  The US Library ofCongress's American Memory program is a most ambitious multimediaproject as the Library attempts to centralize its collection ofsound recordings, motion pictures and photographs with text ontoCD-ROM and videodisc.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   International Business Machines Corp. (Products)Winnebago Software Co. (Product development).andO;Ticker:    IBM.andO;Product:   Mammals: A Multimedia Encyclopedia (Educational software) (Usage)New Grolier Electronic Encyclopedia (Data base) (Usage)The Video Encyclopedia of the 20th Century (Data base) (Usage).andO;Topic:     Multimedia TechnologyCD-ROMEducational SoftwareMultimedia SoftwareData BasesArchival StorageUnited States. Library of Congress.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>